    <abstract>Stelae prohibition in the South since Cao Cao (155-220). Southern Qi emperor Wudi (r.
        483-93) reissued the prohibition. p. 330: In contrast to the north, many rural areas of
        early medieval southern China were governed by a strict mutual responsibility system known
        as the “five tallies” 符伍, which appears to have constrained the formation of all manner of
        socioreligious groups, including Buddhist associations.</abstract>
